{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626476"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:38:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:38:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17078"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17078","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17078"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.11,0.02,0.02,0.76]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9768"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77595"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9768"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17078"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63108"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"},{"type":"tags","id":"5260"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22946"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23190"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77595"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMacrolide antibiotics are commonly prescribed for respiratory tract infections and as alternatives for patients with penicillin allergy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of macrolide antibiotics?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits bacterial cell membrane synthesis","Inhibits bacterial peptidoglycan assembly","Inhibits bacterial topoisomerase enzyme","Inhibits bacterial tetrahydrofolate synthesis","Inhibits bacterial protein synthesis at 50S ribosome"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMacrolide antibiotics work by \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibiting bacterial protein synthesis at 50S ribosome\u003C/strong\u003E in bacteria. This prevents the formation of new proteins necessary for bacterial growth and reproduction, making macrolides bacteriostatic rather than bactericidal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits bacterial cell membrane synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of polymyxin antibiotics, which act by disrupting the bacterial cell membrane structure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits bacterial peptidoglycan assembly\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of beta-lactam antibiotics such as penicillins and cephalosporins, which interfere with cell wall synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits bacterial topoisomerase enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of fluoroquinolone antibiotics, which prevent bacterial DNA replication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits bacterial tetrahydrofolate synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of sulfonamides and trimethoprim, which interfere with bacterial folate metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon examples of macrolide antibiotics include erythromycin, clarithromycin, and azithromycin. They are particularly useful against atypical organisms like \u003Cem\u003EMycoplasma pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003ELegionella pneumophila\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Macrolide antibiotics work by binding to the 50S ribosomal subunit and blocking protein synthesis in bacteria.","Macrolides are bacteriostatic antibiotics that prevent bacterial growth rather than directly killing bacteria.","Common examples of macrolide antibiotics include erythromycin, clarithromycin, and azithromycin."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63108"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17078"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63108"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T20:08:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T20:10:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9768"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77595"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attribute